# Git Automation

## When to commit (default: always after validate)

After `npm run validate` passes:

1. If there are changes → **commit automatically** (no extra user prompt needed).
2. If working tree clean → skip commit, report done.

Do **not** commit if validation failed or only build artifacts changed.

Never commit `.next/`, `out/`, `node_modules/`, `.env*`.

## Commit workflow

Run in parallel first:

```bash
git status
git diff
git log -3 --oneline
```

Then sequentially:

```bash
git add <relevant-files>
git commit -F .git/COMMIT_EDITMSG
# or: git commit -m "type(scope): summary"
git status
```

On Windows PowerShell, prefer message file or single `-m` line if heredoc fails.

## Message format

Use conventional commits:

| Type | Use for |
|------|---------|
| `feat` | New feature or section |
| `fix` | Bug fix |
| `style` | Visual/CSS only |
| `perf` | Performance |
| `refactor` | Code restructure, no behavior change |
| `chore` | Tooling, deps, CI, agent rules |

Example: `feat(hero): add scroll reveal to capabilities section`

## Safety (never)

- `git push --force` to main/master
- `git commit --amend` unless HEAD was your commit and not pushed
- `--no-verify` / `--no-gpg-sign`
- Committing secrets or build output

## Push

Only push when user explicitly asks. Use `git push -u origin HEAD` for new branches.
